Running a business as a solo introverted creative who values their private life shouldn't be complicated, but sometimes it is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with the big (and diabolical) technology companies using extrovert techniques: make advertising here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service checked, be available 24/7, respond to questions with a video of yourself, respond right away. Video, video, video.
01/03/2024
This is a year of transition for me.
I don't want to feed the big technology companies with my money, my data, and my energy. Or have coaches who only have one extrovert solution that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my activity while fighting the idea I used to believe in, that you have to do things a certain way to succeed.
Wish me good luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I've left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I've also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday and it feels good.
Recently, I subscribed to a European-based CRM for better GDPR handling, and I will transfer my activity over the next few weeks.
I've transferred my MX to Proton and I'm now fully enjoying SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
03/03/2024
